{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionLarge Language Models (LLMs) such as GPT-4, Falcon, and LLaMA-2 have revolutionized natural language processing by achieving state-of-the-art results on tasks including question answering, summarization, code generation, and multi-step reasoning.",
    "These models, trained with hundreds of billions of tokens and comprising billions of parameters, exhibit remarkable generalization and instruction-following capabilities.",
    "However, their scale imposes a significant barrier: fully fine-tuning these models for downstream tasks is computationally expensive and memory-intensive, often requiring high-end GPUs and large-scale infrastructure.",
    "This makes full-model adaptation inaccessible for independent researchers, small organizations, and most academic labs.To alleviate this burden, Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) techniques have become increasingly popular.",
    "PEFT freezes the majority of the base model and introduces small, task-specific trainable modules such as adapters or prefix tokens."
  ]
}